The '''white-fronted scops owl''' ('''''Otus sagittatus''''') is a small Asian [[owl]] in the family [[Strigidae]]. It has a declining [[Population (biology)|population]] about which little is known, and is dependent on [[lowland]] and [[foothill]] [[forest]]s which are rapidly being destroyed. This species of owl is considered [[vulnerable species|vulnerable]] and has a population of about 2,500–10,000. It is found in the west of [[Thailand]] and also in peninsular [[Malaysia]].<ref name="iucn status"/> Its range covers {{Convert|149000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}} of [[forest]] at altitudes of {{Convert|0|-|700|m|ft|-2|abbr=on}} above [[sea-level]].

The white-fronted scops owl was [[Species description|described]] by the American ornithologist [[John Cassin]] in 1849 and given the [[binomial name]] ''Ephialtes sagittatus''.<ref>{{ cite journal | last= Cassin | first=John | author-link=John Cassin | year=1849 | title=Species of owls, presumed to be undescribed, specimens of which are in the collection of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia | journal=Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia | volume=4 | pages=121–125 [121] | url= https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/5445384 }} The title page is dated 1848 but the volume was not published until the following year.</ref><ref>{{ cite book | editor-last=Peters | editor-first=James Lee | editor-link=James L. Peters | year=1940 | title=Check-list of Birds of the World | volume=4 | publisher=Harvard University Press | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts  | page=87 | url= https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14476558 }}</ref> The species is [[monotypic]].<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | year=2017 | title=Owls | work=World Bird List Version 7.3 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/owls/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | access-date=23 December 2017 }}</ref>

This kind of owl has two modes of defense. The first is that it can puff up its feathers to triple its body size. The second is that it can stretch its body upwards and turn its head at an angle in the direction of the predator that it is hiding from, reducing visibility.{{Citation needed|date=March 2026}}

